Question

A canoe travels 1.5 m/s relative to the water. A river, heading east, flows at 3.3 m/s. The canoe points at a direction 1.00 radians counterclockwise from east.


Find the canoes total speed, in m/s, and direction of travel, as radians counterclockwise from east.

  • Speed = ##ANSWER1##
  • Direction = ##ANSWER2##

Answerlist

  • 3.8
  • 3.9
  • 4.0
  • 4.1
  • 4.2
  • 4.3
  • 0.27
  • 0.28
  • 0.29
  • 0.30
  • 0.31
  • 0.32

Solution

First, find the rectangular coordinates of each velocity vector. The two formulas:

\[x~=~r\cdot\cos(\theta)\] \[y~=~r\cdot\sin(\theta)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_1\) for the canoes velocity relative to water. It is shown below with approximate rectangular coordinates (found from formulas above, using \(r=1.5\) and \(\theta=1.00\)).

\[\vec{v}_1 = (0.810,1.262)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_2\) for the rivers velocity vector. Since the river flows directly east, all of its speed is in the positive horizontal direction.

\[\vec{v}_2 = (3.300,0.000)\]

Now, add the corresponding components to find \(\vec{v}_3\), the velocity of the canoe relative to the ground.

\[\vec{v}_3 = (4.110,1.262)\]

Lastly, we need to find the polar coordinates. The formulas are given below. Notice, I am using the two-argument arctangent function.

\[r~=~\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\] \[\theta~=~\arctan(y,x)\]

So,

\[r=\sqrt{(4.110)^2+(1.262)^2}~=~4.2998829\]

\[\theta=\arctan(1.262,4.110)~=~0.2979325\]

This can be visualized.
